The random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, with \(X \sim N(5, 16)\) and \(Y \sim N(6, 9)\). The goal is to evaluate \(P(X > Y) = P(X - Y > 0)\).

The difference \(X - Y\) follows a normal distribution because \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent normal random variables. The mean of \(X - Y\) is \(E[X] - E[Y] = 5 - 6 = -1\). The variance of \(X - Y\) is \(\text{Var}(X) + \text{Var}(Y) = 16 + 9 = 25\), so the standard deviation is \(\sqrt{25} = 5\).

Thus, \(X - Y \sim N(-1, 25)\). The probability \(P(X - Y > 0)\) is standardized using the z-score:
\[
Z = \frac{(X - Y) - (-1)}{5} = \frac{X - Y + 1}{5}.
\]
Then,
\[
P(X - Y > 0) = P\left(Z > \frac{0 - (-1)}{5}\right) = P\left(Z > \frac{1}{5}\right) = P(Z > 0.2),
\]
where \(Z\) is a standard normal random variable.

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z < 0.2)\). The cumulative distribution function value \(P(Z < 0.2) \approx 0.5793\), so:
\[
P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207.
\]
Rounded to three decimal places, the result is 0.421.

