 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for any one of the three drugs exceeds eight, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and is tested in 10 independent trials (one per triple over 10 triples).

The number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). Let \(S_1\), \(S_2\), and \(S_3\) represent the number of successes for drugs 1, 2, and 3, respectively. These are independent and identically distributed.

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds eight is \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8)\). This is equivalent to \(1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8)\), which simplifies to \(1 - [P(S \leq 8)]^3\), where \(S \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\).

First, compute \(P(S \leq 8)\):
- \(P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S \leq 8) = 1 - P(S = 9) - P(S = 10) = 1 - 0.121060821 - 0.0282475249 = 0.8506916541\)

Then, \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = [P(S \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3\):
- \((0.8506916541)^2 = 0.723675734417931\)
- \((0.723675734417931) \times 0.8506916541 = 0.6156249075119897\)
- So, \(P(\max \leq 8) \approx 0.6156249075\)

Thus, \(P(\max > 8) = 1 - 0.6156249075 = 0.3843750925\).

Rounded to three significant figures, this is 0.384.

