**************
The solution calculates the probability \(P(52.761 \leq \bar{X} \leq 54.453)\) for the sample mean \(\bar{X}\) using the Central Limit Theorem. The sampling distribution of \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normal with mean \(\mu_{\bar{X}} = 54.030\) and standard error \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = 5.8 / \sqrt{47} \approx 0.846\). The z-scores are computed as \(z_1 = (52.761 - 54.030) / 0.846 \approx -1.5\) and \(z_2 = (54.453 - 54.030) / 0.846 \approx 0.5\). The probability \(P(-1.5 \leq Z \leq 0.5)\) is found using standard normal distribution tables, resulting in \(0.6915 - 0.0668 = 0.6247\), rounded to four decimal places.

The final answer is a probability and is dimensionless, so no unit is specified.

