Solution: The dissociation energy \(D_e\) is calculated from the given \(D_0 = 2.4287 \, \text{eV}\), \(\omega_e = \nu_e / c = 1405.65 \, \text{cm}^{-1}\), and \(\omega_e x_e = \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20 \, \text{cm}^{-1}\), where \(\omega_e\) and \(\omega_e x_e\) are the standard spectroscopic constants.

The zero-point energy (ZPE) in wavenumber units is given by:
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e
\]
Substituting the values:
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 702.825 - 5.800 = 697.025 \, \text{cm}^{-1}
\]

Convert ZPE to eV using the conversion factor \(1 \, \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{eV}\):
\[
\text{ZPE} = 697.025 \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} = 0.086420 \, \text{eV}
\]

Then, \(D_e\) is:
\[
D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE} = 2.4287 + 0.086420 = 2.515120 \, \text{eV}
\]

Considering significant figures and precision, \(D_0 = 2.4287 \, \text{eV}\) has four decimal places, and the calculation uncertainty supports rounding \(D_e\) to four decimal places, resulting in \(2.5151 \, \text{eV}\).

